e class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://haiduongblog.cf/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/loog.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-32\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While this pandemic and subsequent shutdown has affected everyone in some way or the other, more and more young people in their mid-20s to early 30s are feeling anxious, uneasy, uninspired, or uncertain in life. While many have lost their jobs, several who had big dreams of kickstarting a fresh career have been finding themselves stuck at home, not being able to do much that keeps them inspired and hopeful for the future. We find out more about quarter life crisis and ways to deal with it<br><strong>NOT BEING ABLE TO MAXIMISE TIME AND OPPORTUNITIES</strong><br>Conventionally, twenties are a phase when we are meant to live our best life by making the most of the presented opportunities prior to settling down and dealing with the stress that comes with middle age. Unfortunately, the younger generation have been undergoing a quarter-life crisis, an emotional condition that is fueled by a host of structural, financial and technical aspects that are beyond one\'s control. \"Quarter-life crisis is a period of strong soul searching and anxiety occurring in your mid-20s to early 30s. The sufferers, although may be highly driven and capable, are struggling because they feel they are not attaining their potential or feeling that they are falling behind. For instance, you may have procured your dream job after your graduation, but you find out that cubicle life has been crushing your creativity or in spite of your highly qualified degree, you are still unemployed due to the pandemic situation,\" says Kanchan Rai, Mental and Emotional Wellbeing Coach . \"Much of the millennial contentment will be based on how they navigate these times of transition and turn the crisis into opportunities,\" adds Rai.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>SOCIAL MEDIA AND CONSTANT COMPARISON</strong>&nbsp;With social media trying to show the best and most successful sides of people\'s lives, it is bound to make you question yours, especially for someone who isn’t emotionally intelligent. \"Each of us must know in our bones that social media is a virtual world. We do not know what\'s really behind the scenes. Everything you see does not have to be real. The lives of most people appear as they have done well, but a lot of them own material things on loan or are living off their parents’ wealth. Several are flaunting clothes, jewellery, cars, etc that don’t really belong to them. So, if you are someone who is comparing every single part of your life with someone else\'s, you are only playing a role in your unhappiness, dissatisfaction, and discontentment. Comparisons are truly a thief of joy,\" says Luke Coutinho, Holistic Lifestyle Coach.<br>Access to information through social media and other platforms has also put a lot of pressure on ourselves to achieve, perform and deliver. \"The result-oriented society that we live in moves us from just focusing on trying and putting in effort to focusing on delivering excellence at all times. While these things sound great in boardrooms, training programs and leadership development courses, it is important to recognize that sometimes high delivery of performance may not always be possible especially when one is pushing themselves to the brink and spreading themselves thin,\" Clinical Psychologist Priyanka Varma.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>THE PANDEMIC AND IT\'S IMPACT ON THE MENTAL WELLNESS OF MILLENIALS</strong><br>The pandemic forced youngsters to spend a lot of time with themselves which in turn led to looking inwards. At the same time, idleness led to negative, often self-deprecating thoughts. Mumbai-based event planner Rachna Kapadia says she often found herself lost in thoughts during the lockdown phase at home. \"With absolutely no work for several months, I\'d often feel like I didn\'t have a purpose in life. Going from extreme busyness to doing nothing was frustrating. With no positive news, I would keep worrying about my future. I felt like time was slipping by and I couldn\'t do anything about it. I\'d often feel lonely and helpless,\" says Kapadia. Taking into consideration the many impacts of the pandemic, possibly the least acknowledged are psychological disturbances among the millennials. \"Some of the reasons behind the younger generations to suffer the most mental anguish amidst the crisis are a constant worry about the well-being of their loved ones, confusion about the uncertainty that surrounds their professional paths, social lives being paused, isolation, and the replacement of in-person and tangible communications with screens. All this has contributed to a rise in despair and depression in the young. The less a person is competent to accept vagueness, the more likely he or she will be to enter anxiety spirals. This ultimately wreaks havoc on our brains and acts as a major depression stressor,\" explains Rai.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While there are absolutely no easy solutions to figure out an appropriate life path, undertaking a couple of baby steps will help you bring in the desired change, routing your thoughts in a positive direction. \"At the same time, it\'s important to know that having negative feelings isn’t abnormal or a disorder. Take it as a phase of life and handle it by seeking support at the right time,\" suggests Coutinho.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Quarter-life Crisis','','publish','closed','closed','','quarter-life-crisis','','','2022-02-17 15:26:03','2022-02-17 15:26:03','',0,'http://haiduongblog.cf/?page_id=30',0,'page','',0),(31,1,'2022-02-17 15:17:06','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','closed','closed','','','','','2022-02-17 15:17:06','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://haiduongblog.cf/?page_id=31',0,'page','',0),(32,1,'